    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-17T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-17T17:00:00-05:00" n="155"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d155">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./125: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-17T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 17, 1934—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>247. Your 304, 305 and 306.<note n="67" xml:id="d155fn67">Telegrams Nos. 305 and
                        306 not printed.</note> Considering that <persName>Litvinoff</persName> when
                    here made no objection to added or extra interest feature, and further that we
                    are not responsible for the Soviet’s relations with England and France, it would
                    seem now obligatory on the Soviet to propose some plan that may conceivably be
                    acceptable, but of course not including a loan or open credit. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGH1">Hackworth</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KRF1"
                        >Kelley</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MRW1">Moore</persName> are
                    unable to vary the concessions we have already made.</p>
                <p>If you think it worth while trying to work out with Soviet Government an
                    acceptable formula, it may be possible for <persName corresp="#p_KRF1"
                        >Kelley</persName>, should you so desire, to be in Moscow around October
                    1.</p>
                <p>Have just mailed the President proposed amendment of his Executive Order designed
                    to relieve you of the exchange trouble.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
